<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="1131" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1131">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.6363/110.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Rear Admiral Sir <persName type="from">C.
                                    Cradock</persName> to the <gloss type="to">British Ambassador at
                                    Washington</gloss>.</hi><note n="96" xml:id="d1131fn96">Handed
                                to the Department of State by the British Ambassador May 7,
                                1914.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Vera Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-07">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 7, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>From the conditions known to me and judging by my own experience I think
                            it would be rash if American citizens relied too implicitly on Mexican
                            assurances and returned now to the oil-fields. Their return might be
                            misunderstood, and a situation might arise which would imperil all
                            foreign interests.</p>
                        <closer>[Unsigned.]</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>